%I A397259 #9 Jul 07 2026 18:43:32
%S A397259 2,3,5,7,11,17,19,23,29,31,41,47,59,61,89,97,113,347,461,503
%N A397259 Late birds in Buss's sequence B = A067836: primes B(m) such that all smaller primes have appeared earlier.
%C A397259 To tackle Buss's conjecture (i.e., all and only primes appear in B = A067836), it is useful to know what are the smallest primes that have not yet appeared up to a given point. These are listed here, while the indices where they appear are given in A397258.
%C A397259 Indeed, a prime factor of B(n) would have to be distinct from all earlier B(k)'s, but must of course be smaller than B(n) which is smaller than the prime gap at f(n).
%C A397259 Conjecturally this is equivalent to say that we list terms a(n) = B(m) such that B(k) > B(m) for all k > m. But we prefer the chosen definition because it makes the sequence unambiguously defined (and finite, in case one prime would never appear in A067836).
%e A397259 a(5) = B(6) = 11 = prime(5) appears only after the larger B(5) = 13 = prime(6).
%e A397259 a(9) = B(12) = 29 = prime(10) appears only after the larger terms B(10) = 37 and B(11) = 73, not after B(9) = 23 = prime(9).
%e A397259 a(20) = 503 = prime(96) appears only at A397258(20) = 3289.
%o A397259 (PARI) my(S=[2]); A397259 = [a|a<-A067836,!if(a>S[1],S=setunion(S,[a]),until(#S==1||S[2]>S[1]||!S=S[^1],S[1]=nextprime(S[1]+1)))]
%Y A397259 Cf. A067836, A397258 (indices of the terms a(n) in A067836).
%K A397259 nonn,more
%O A397259 1,1
%A A397259 _M. F. Hasler_, Jun 22 2026
